  "prompt": "Should I put osha certificate in my mechanical resume?",
  "response": "Including an OSHA (Occupational Safety and Health Administration) certificate on your mechanical resume can be beneficial, especially if:\n\n1. The job requires or prefers safety certifications\n2. The position is in an industry where safety is critical\n3. The specific OSHA certificate is relevant to the job\n\nTypical OSHA certificates that might be valuable include:\n- OSHA 10-hour Construction Safety\n- OSHA 30-hour General Industry Safety\n- Specific safety training certifications\n\nTips for including OSHA certificates:\n- Place it in a \"Certifications\" or \"Training\" section\n- Specify the exact certificate name and date of certification\n- Highlight if it's particularly relevant to the job description\n\nExample:\nCertifications:\n- OSHA 30-hour General Industry Safety Certification, 2022\n\nIf you're unsure, review the job description or consult with industry professionals in your field to determine the certificate's relevance.",
